            <section>
                <h2>Singleton Pattern for State Management</h2>
                <p>
                    The <strong>Singleton pattern</strong> ensures that a class has only one instance and provides a global point of access to it.
                    In this example, the <code>ThemeManager</code> is implemented as a Singleton. This means there's only one instance of <code>ThemeManager</code>
                    throughout the entire application, and all parts of the code that need to manage or retrieve the current theme will interact with this
                    single instance.
                </p>
                <h3>How it Works Here:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>The <code>ThemeManager</code> class has a private constructor to prevent direct instantiation.</li>
                    <li>A static method (e.g., <code>getInstance()</code>) is used to create and return the single instance. If an instance already exists, it returns the existing one.</li>
                    <li>It stores the current theme state (e.g., 'light' or 'dark').</li>
                    <li>It provides methods to toggle the theme (<code>toggleTheme()</code>) and retrieve the current theme (<code>getTheme()</code>).</li>
                    <li>When the theme is toggled, it updates the <code>body</code> class (<code>light-theme</code> or <code>dark-theme</code>) to apply the appropriate CSS styles.</li>
                    <li>It also persists the theme preference in <code>localStorage</code> so it remembers your choice across page loads.</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Pros of using Singleton for Theme Management:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Global Access:</strong> Any component, anywhere in your application, can easily access the single theme manager instance to get or set the theme without needing to pass it around.</li>
                    <li><strong>Guaranteed Single Instance:</strong> You are certain there's only one source of truth for the current theme, preventing inconsistencies.</li>
                    <li><strong>Resource Management:</strong> If the theme manager involved complex initialization or resource loading, a Singleton ensures this happens only once.</li>
                    <li><strong>Simplicity for Small Apps:</strong> For simpler applications, it can be a quick and easy way to manage global state.</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Cons of using Singleton for Theme Management:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Global State:</strong> While convenient, global state can make applications harder to reason about, test, and debug. Any part of the code can modify the theme, leading to unexpected behavior.</li>
                    <li><strong>Tight Coupling:</strong> Components directly depend on the concrete <code>ThemeManager</code> class and its <code>getInstance()</code> method. This creates tight coupling, making it harder to swap out the theme management logic or test components in isolation.</li>
                    <li><strong>Difficult to Test:</strong> Because of tight coupling and global state, unit testing components that rely on the Singleton can be challenging. You might need to reset the Singleton's state between tests.</li>
                    <li><strong>Violates Single Responsibility Principle (SRP):</strong> The Singleton pattern often combines the responsibility of the class itself with the responsibility of ensuring a single instance.</li>
                    <li><strong>Scalability Issues:</strong> In larger, more complex applications, relying heavily on Singletons can lead to an "God Object" anti-pattern, where a single object becomes responsible for too much.</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>When Dependency Injection (DI) would be a better choice:</h3>
                <p>
                    <strong>Dependency Injection</strong> is a technique where objects receive their dependencies from an external source rather than creating them themselves.
                    Instead of a component calling <code>ThemeManager.getInstance()</code>, the <code>ThemeManager</code> instance would be "injected" into the component.
                </p>
                <p>DI would be a better choice for theme management (and most other services) in scenarios where:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Testability is paramount:</strong> With DI, you can easily inject mock or stub theme managers during testing, allowing you to isolate and test components without relying on the actual theme logic.</li>
                    <li><strong>Flexibility and Extensibility are needed:</strong> If you foresee needing different theme management strategies (e.g., fetching themes from an API, complex user preferences, multiple themes), DI allows you to easily swap out implementations without changing the consuming components.</li>
                    <li><strong>Reduced Coupling:</strong> Components depend on an abstraction (an interface or abstract class) rather than a concrete implementation. This makes your codebase more modular and easier to maintain.</li>
                    <li><strong>Larger, Enterprise Applications:</strong> In complex systems, DI frameworks (like Angular's DI, or simple manual DI) help manage the lifecycle and dependencies of many services, leading to a more organized and scalable architecture.</li>
                    <li><strong>Clearer Dependency Graph:</strong> It becomes explicit what dependencies each component needs, improving code readability and maintainability.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    <strong>Example of DI Thinking:</strong> Instead of a component doing `const themeManager = ThemeManager.getInstance();`, it would receive `themeManager` as a constructor argument: `class MyComponent { constructor(themeManager) { this.themeManager = themeManager; } }`. The responsibility of providing that `themeManager` instance would fall to a higher-level "injector" or "container".
                </p>
