        <section class="discussion-section">
            <h2>Discussion: Singleton Design Pattern</h2>

            <p>The Singleton pattern ensures that a class has only one instance and provides a global point of access to that instance. In this demo, the `ThemeManager` is a singleton.</p>

            <h3>Advantages of Singletons:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Controlled Access to Single Instance:</strong> Ensures that there's only one instance of a class, which is crucial for resources like theme managers, loggers, or database connections where multiple instances could lead to conflicts or inconsistent state.</li>
                <li><strong>Global Access:</strong> Provides a well-known global access point to the instance, making it easy to retrieve and use from anywhere in the application (e.g., `ThemeManager.getInstance().setTheme('dark')`).</li>
                <li><strong>Lazy Initialization:</strong> The instance is typically created only when it's first requested, saving resources if the instance is not always needed.</li>
                <li><strong>State Management:</strong> Ideal for managing application-wide state, like the current theme, user authentication status, or configuration settings.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Disadvantages of Singletons:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Global State (God Object Anti-Pattern):</strong> Introduces global state, which can make testing difficult. Components become tightly coupled to the singleton, making it hard to isolate them for unit testing (mocking singletons can be tricky).</li>
                <li><strong>Hidden Dependencies:</strong> A component that uses a singleton has a hidden dependency on it. This makes the code harder to understand, maintain, and refactor, as dependencies are not explicitly declared.</li>
                <li><strong>Difficulty in Testing:</strong> Because singletons persist their state across tests, one test might inadvertently affect the outcome of another, leading to brittle and unreliable tests. Resetting singleton state between tests can be cumbersome.</li>
                <li><strong>Violates Single Responsibility Principle (SRP):</strong> Often, singletons take on too many responsibilities (managing their own creation and their core logic), violating SRP.</li>
                <li><strong>Concurrency Issues:</strong> In multi-threaded environments (less common in typical browser JS, but relevant for Web Workers or Node.js), careful synchronization is needed to prevent race conditions during instance creation.</li>
                <li><strong>Scalability Issues:</strong> Can become a bottleneck if the single instance is accessed frequently by many parts of the application, especially if its operations are complex.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>When Dependency Injection or Alternatives are More Appropriate:</h3>
            <p>While singletons offer convenience, their drawbacks often outweigh the benefits, especially in larger, more complex, or test-driven applications. Here's when alternatives are better:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Testability is Paramount:</strong> If you need to easily mock or swap out dependencies for unit testing, Dependency Injection (DI) is far superior. With DI, you pass dependencies into a component's constructor or setter methods, allowing you to inject mock objects during tests.</li>
                <li><strong>Flexibility and Reusability:</strong> When components might need different configurations or implementations of a service, DI allows you to provide them dynamically. Singletons lock you into one global instance.</li>
                <li><strong>Avoiding Global State:</strong> For most application components, avoiding global state leads to cleaner, more predictable, and easier-to-debug code. Pass necessary services as arguments or through DI containers.</li>
                <li><strong>Explicit Dependencies:</strong> DI makes dependencies explicit, improving code readability and maintainability. You immediately see what a component needs to function.</li>
                <li><strong>Service Locator Pattern:</strong> A less strict alternative to DI, where a "Service Locator" object knows how to obtain services. It still introduces a global access point but can be more flexible than a strict singleton if services can be registered/unregistered. However, it still suffers from some of the same hidden dependency issues as singletons.</li>
                <li><strong>Module Pattern / IIFEs:</strong> In JavaScript, for simple "single instance" needs that don't require complex class instantiation, the module pattern (using IIFEs or ES6 modules) can provide private state and public methods without the explicit singleton class structure, often leading to cleaner code.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>In summary, while a singleton might seem convenient for something like a `ThemeManager` (as demonstrated here), it's crucial to weigh the immediate convenience against the long-term maintainability and testability concerns it introduces, especially for critical or complex parts of an application.</p>
