                <h2>Understanding the Singleton Pattern</h2>
                <p>
                    The Singleton pattern ensures that a class has only one instance and provides a global point of access to it.
                    In this example, our <code>ThemeManager</code> is implemented as a singleton to manage the current theme state.
                    This means that no matter how many times we try to get an instance of <code>ThemeManager</code>, we will always
                    receive the same single instance, ensuring consistent theme state across the application.
                </p>

                <h3>Pros of the Singleton Pattern:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Guaranteed Single Instance:</strong> Ensures that a class has only one instance, which is useful for
                        objects like configuration managers, loggers, or (as here) theme managers, where a single, centralized point of control is desired.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Global Access:</strong> Provides a global access point to that instance, making it easy for different parts of the application
                        to interact with it without passing the instance around.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Lazy Initialization:</strong> The instance can be created only when it's first needed, saving resources if the instance is
                        not always used.
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Cons of the Singleton Pattern:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Global State:</strong> Introduces global state, which can make testing difficult (due to tightly coupled components and
                        hard-to-isolate tests) and lead to unforeseen side effects.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Tight Coupling:</strong> Components that directly call <code>Singleton.getInstance()</code> become tightly coupled to the
                        Singleton class, reducing flexibility and reusability.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Violates Single Responsibility Principle:</strong> A singleton class often takes on more than one responsibility:
                        managing its own instance and performing its core business logic.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Hard to Mock/Test:</strong> Because you can't easily swap out a singleton instance for a mock during testing,
                        it can complicate unit testing.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Scalability Issues:</strong> In multi-threaded environments (though less common in client-side JS),
                        extra care is needed to ensure thread safety during instance creation.
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <div class="highlight">
                    <h4>When to use (and when not to use) Singletons:</h4>
                    <p>
                        Use singletons sparingly and for truly global, unique resources like a core configuration service or, as shown here,
                        a simple theme manager in a small application.
                        <strong>Avoid them for managing application state that could vary or for services that might need different implementations.</strong>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        For more complex applications, or when testability and flexibility are paramount, alternatives like
                        <strong>Dependency Injection (DI)</strong> are generally preferred.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <h3>Alternatives: Dependency Injection</h3>
                <p>
                    <strong>Dependency Injection (DI)</strong> is a design pattern in which a class receives its dependencies from an external source,
                    rather than creating them itself. Instead of a component directly calling <code>ThemeManager.getInstance()</code>,
                    a <code>ThemeManager</code> instance would be "injected" into the component (e.g., via its constructor or a setter method).
                </p>
                <p>
                    <strong>Why DI is often better:</strong>
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Improved Testability:</strong> You can easily inject mock or stub implementations of dependencies during testing,
                        isolating the component under test.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Reduced Coupling:</strong> Components don't know how their dependencies are created, only that they exist.
                        This makes them more reusable and easier to refactor.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Increased Flexibility:</strong> It's easier to swap out different implementations of a service without changing
                        the consuming components.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Clearer Dependencies:</strong> Dependencies are explicitly declared, making it clearer what a component needs to function.
                    </li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    While the Singleton pattern is simple for this small example, understanding its limitations and knowing when to opt for more robust
                    patterns like Dependency Injection is crucial for building maintainable and scalable applications.
                </p>
            </section>
