            <h2>Understanding the Singleton Design Pattern</h2>
            <p>
                The Singleton is a creational design pattern that restricts the instantiation of a class to a single object. This is useful when exactly one object is needed to coordinate actions across the system.
            </p>

            <h3>Pros of the Singleton Pattern:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Controlled Access to Single Instance:</strong> It ensures that there's only one instance of the class, preventing multiple, potentially conflicting, instances.</li>
                <li><strong>Global Access Point:</strong> Provides a well-known global access point to that single instance, making it easy to retrieve from anywhere in the application.</li>
                <li><strong>Lazy Initialization:</strong> The instance can be created only when it's first requested, saving resources if the instance is not always needed.</li>
                <li><strong>Resource Management:</strong> Ideal for managing shared resources like a database connection, a logger, or in our case, a global theme state.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Cons of the Singleton Pattern:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Global State (Anti-Pattern):</strong> Introduces global state, which can make testing difficult (due to tightly coupled components) and lead to unforeseen side effects.</li>
                <li><strong>Tight Coupling:</strong> Components directly depend on the concrete singleton class, making it hard to swap out implementations or mock for testing.</li>
                <li><strong>Violation of Single Responsibility Principle:</strong> The class not only manages its core logic but also controls its own instantiation.</li>
                <li><strong>Difficulty in Testing:</strong> Because it's globally accessible and often mutable, resetting its state between tests can be challenging.</li>
                <li><strong>Potential for Misuse:</strong> Can be overused for convenience, leading to systems that are hard to maintain and extend.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>When are Alternatives like Dependency Injection Better?</h3>
            <p>
                While Singletons have their place, modern software development often favors alternatives like <strong>Dependency Injection (DI)</strong>, especially for larger, more complex applications or when testability is paramount.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Dependency Injection</strong> is a technique where an object receives other objects that it depends on ("dependencies"). These dependencies are "injected" into the object by an external entity (e.g., a framework or a manual factory) rather than the object creating them itself.
            </p>
            <h4>Why DI is often preferred:</h4>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Improved Testability:</strong> You can easily inject mock or stub implementations of dependencies during testing, isolating the component under test.</li>
                <li><strong>Reduced Coupling:</strong> Components are less coupled because they don't know how their dependencies are created; they just know they'll receive them.</li>
                <li><strong>Increased Flexibility and Maintainability:</strong> It's easier to swap out different implementations of a dependency without modifying the consuming class.</li>
                <li><strong>Better Readability:</strong> Dependencies are explicitly declared, making it clear what a component needs to function.</li>
                <li><strong>Scalability:</strong> Promotes a modular architecture that is easier to scale and manage as the application grows.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                For our simple theme manager, a singleton is a straightforward and understandable approach. However, if this were part of a larger application with complex state, multiple themes, or a need for extensive unit testing, a DI approach (e.g., passing the <code>ThemeManager</code> instance to components that need it, or using a dedicated state management library) would likely be a more robust and maintainable choice.
            </p>
